# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-ramcharger
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] There are many types of car body styles.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] They vary depending on intended use, market position, location, and the era they were made.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Lightweight off-road vehicle with sparse bodywork.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Originally two- or four-wheeled carriages in the 19th and early 20th centuries pulled by one horse, the motorized buggies were developed in the 1960s and grew in popularity and diversity.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A convertible allows an open-air driving experience, with the ability to provide a roof when required.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Most convertible roofs are either a folding textile soft-top or a retractable metal roof.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Convertibles with a metal roof are sometimes called 'retractable hardtop', 'coupé convertible', or 'coupé cabriolet'.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Two-door car, seating up to four persons.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Some two-door cars have only two seats, thus **two-seaters**.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Type of SUV with a sloping roofline similar to fastback cars, That is often adopted to offer a styling advantage compared to standard SUVs.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Manufacturers often sell them as more premium models than their standard SUV counterparts.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Vehicle with a higher ground clearence and larger space, That is built in a unibody platform shared with standard cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Originally a North American term used for vehicles that blend characteristics between two types, it evolved to be a term for SUVs built in a unibody chassis, Even though the term SUV is used to refer both to crossovers and standard SUVs due to their visual similarities.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Car with a roofline that slopes continuously down at the back.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] The design features a single unbroken convex curve from the roof to the rear.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Used in the U.S. in the funeral industry to carry flowers for burial services.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Typically a coupé-style, forward-passenger compartment with an open well in the rear.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Car with a hatch-type rear door that is hinged at the roof and opens upwards.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] The term "hatchback" can also refer to that type of rear door, which is also used on several sports cars, SUVs, and large luxury cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] The modification of a passenger car to provide a long cargo area for carrying a coffin or casket.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Hearses often have large glass panels for viewing the coffin.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A vehicle that combines characteristics and styling of a sedan with a higher ground clearance, Similar to a crossover.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A Kammback is a car where the rear slopes downwards before being abruptly cut off with a vertical or near vertical surface.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] This reduces the aerodynamic drag, improving the efficiency, while the stil keeping its traditional shape.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Variant of a hatchback where the roof line and the rear cargo door are more horizontal than vertical.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A luxury-type vehicle that is typically driven by a chauffeur with a partition between the driver's compartment and the passenger's compartment.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Limousines may also be stretched to provide more room in the rear passenger compartment.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] In some European usage, the word describes a regular four-door sedan body style.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Vehicle designed to transport passengers in the rear seating row(s) with reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Typically has a combined passenger and cargo area, a high roof, a flat floor, a sliding door for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] In Europe, some small minivans have been marketed as 'leisure activity vehicles'.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Car with a distinct rear section, With the back of the passenger compartment being in an angle to the top of what is generally the baggage compartment.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A cargo vehicle based upon passenger car chassis and typically has one row of seats with no side windows at the rear.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A panel van is smaller than a panel truck or cargo van and is often built on a car platform.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A panel truck is a larger version of the panel van and is often built on a heavier platform.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] In South Africa, a pickup truck is called a "bakkie".
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] An open two-seat car with emphasis on sporting appearance or character.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Initially, an American term for a two-seat car with no weather protection, usage has spread internationally and has evolved to include two-seat convertibles.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] These form separate compartments for engine, passenger, and cargo.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A sedan is called a "berlina" in Spanish and Italian, or a "berline" in French.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Initially, a horse-drawn vehicle used to carry shooting parties with their equipment and game; subsequently synonymous with station wagon / estate car; and in contemporary usage a three- or five-door wagon combining features of a station wagon and a coupé.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Type of vehicle that combines characteristics of a passenger car with a offroad vehicle, like higher ground clearence and four wheel drive.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Has a two-box design, a large cargo area, and a rear tailgate that is hinged to open for access to the cargo area.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] The body style is similar to a hatchback car; however, station wagons are longer and are more likely to have the roofline extended to the rear of the car (resulting in a vertical rear surface to the car) to maximize the cargo space.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] In French, a station wagon is called a "break".
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A semi-convertible style used on some sports cars, featuring a fully removable soft or hard roof panel that leaves the A and B pillars in place on the car body.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Based on a passenger sedan chassis and has a cargo tray in the rear integrated with the passenger body (as opposed to a pickup truck, which has a separate cargo tray).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] In Australia, the term "ute" was originally used solely for coupé utility cars; however, in recent years, it has also been used for pickup trucks.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Has two rows of raised seats, similar to horse-drawn carriages; usually did not have front doors, a roof, or a windshield.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] The baquet ("bathtub") style was produced in the early 1900s in Europe.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Also a marketing term used on cars built in the United States in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Italian two-seat sports car with either an open-top or convertible roof.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] The term was originally used for lightweight open-top racing cars from the late 1940s through the 1950s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Since the 1950s, the name barchetta ("little boat" in Italian) has been revived on several occasions, mostly for cars with convertible roofs that are not specifically intended for racing.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Italian sports coupé, typically with two seats but also including 2+2 cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A retractable textile roof, similar to a convertible/cabriolet.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] The difference is that where a convertible often has the B-pillar, C-pillar, and other bodywork removed, the cabrio-coach retains all bodywork to the top of the door frames and just replaces the roof skin with a retractable fabric panel.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Some modern cars, Like the Fiat 500 (2007), featured this body style.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] An external or open-topped driver's position and an enclosed compartment for passengers.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Although the different terms may have once had specific meanings for certain car manufacturers or countries, the terms are often used interchangeably.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Some coupé de villes have the passengers separated from the driver in a fully enclosed compartment, while others have a canopy for the passengers and no partition between the driver and the passengers (therefore passengers enter the compartment via the driver's area).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Usually describes pillarless hardtops that are cars without a B-pillar often styled to give the appearance of a convertible.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Popular in the United States from the mid 1950s through the mid 1970s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] It also refers to a separate top that is removable and made of metal or other hard material for sports cars or small SUVs.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A car where the rear passengers are covered by a convertible top.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Often the driver is separated from the rear passengers with a partition, as per a limousine.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] American luxury coupés and convertibles produced from 1952 to 2007.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] The cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] An open-roof automobile without any fixed weather protection, which was popular from the 1900s until the 1930s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] An open-topped roadster body and a rear cargo bed.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A light, inexpensive, open car with basic bodywork and no windshield, top, or doors.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Most runabouts had just a single row of seats, providing seating for two passengers.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] Body style was a type of automobile body used from 1908 until the mid-1930s, which had a streamlined profile and a folding or detachable soft top.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] The design consists of a hood or bonnet line raised to be level with the car's waistline, resulting in a straight beltline from front to back.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] A style of open car built in the United States that seats four or more people.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-body-style] The style was popular from the early 1900s to the 1930s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Governments and private organizations have developed **car classification** schemes that are used for various purposes including regulation, description, and categorization of cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The International Standard ISO 3833-1977 *Road vehicles – Types – Terms and definitions* also defines terms for classifying cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The following table summarises the commonly used terms of market segments and legal classifications.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Microcars and their Japanese equivalent— kei cars— are the smallest category of automobile.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Microcars straddle the boundary between car and motorbike, and are often covered by separate regulations from normal cars, resulting in relaxed requirements for registration and licensing.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Engine size is often 700 cc (43 cu in) or less, and microcars have three or four wheels.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Microcars are most popular in Europe, where they originated following World War II.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The predecessors to micro cars are voiturettes and cycle cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Kei cars have been used in Japan since 1949.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The smallest category of vehicles that are registered as normal cars is called A-segment in Europe, or "city car" in Europe and the United States.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency defines this category as "minicompact." However, this term is not widely used.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The equivalents of A-segment cars have been produced since the early 1920s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] However, the category increased in popularity in the late 1950s when the original Fiat 500 and BMC Mini were released.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The next larger category of small cars is called B-segment in Europe, supermini in the United Kingdom and subcompact in the United States.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The size of a subcompact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of between 85–99 cubic feet (2,410–2,800 L).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Since the EPA's smaller minicompact category is not as commonly used by the general public, A-segment cars are sometimes called subcompacts in the United States.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] In Europe and Great Britain, the B-segment and supermini categories do not have any formal definitions based on size.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Early supermini cars in Great Britain include the 1977 Ford Fiesta and Vauxhall Chevette.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] In the United States, the first locally-built subcompact cars were the 1970 AMC Gremlin, Chevrolet Vega, and Ford Pinto.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The largest category of small cars is called *C-segment* or *small family car* in Europe, and *compact car* in the United States.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The size of a compact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of 100–109 cu ft (2.8–3.1 m3).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] In Europe, the third-largest category for passenger cars is called *D-segment* or *large family car*.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] In the United States, the equivalent term is *mid-size* or *intermediate* cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) defines a mid-size car as having a combined passenger and cargo volume of 110–119 cu ft (3.1–3.4 m3).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] In Europe, the second-largest category for passenger cars is E-segment / executive car, which are usually luxury cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] In other countries, the equivalent terms are *full-size car* or *large car*, which are also used for relatively affordable large cars that are not considered luxury cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Minivan is an American car classification for vehicles that are designed to transport passengers in the rear seating rows, and have reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The equivalent terms in British English are multi-purpose vehicle (MPV), people carrier, and people mover.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Minivans are often of the "one-box" or "two-box" body configuration, high roofs, flat floors, sliding doors for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Mini MPV is the smallest size of MPVs and the vehicles are often built on the platforms of B-segment hatchback models.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The compact MPV size class includes vehicles between the mini MPV and large MPV (minivan) sizes.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Compact MPVs remain predominantly a European phenomenon, although they are also built and sold in many Latin American and Asian markets.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The largest size of minivans is also referred to as "large MPV" and became popular following the introduction of the 1984 Renault Espace and Dodge Caravan.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Since the 1990s, the smaller compact MPV and mini MPV sizes of minivans have also become popular.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] If the term "minivan" is used without specifying a size, it usually refers to a large MPV.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The premium compact class (also called subcompact executive) is the smallest category of luxury cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] It became popular in the mid-2000s, when European manufacturers — such as Audi, BMW, and Mercedes-Benz — introduced new entry-level models that were smaller and cheaper than their compact executive models.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] A compact executive car or a compact luxury car is a premium car larger than a *premium compact* and smaller than an *executive car*.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Compact executive cars are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] In North American terms, close equivalents are "luxury compact" and "entry-level luxury car", although the latter is also used for the smaller *premium compact cars*.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] An executive car is a premium car larger than a *compact executive* and smaller than a *full-size luxury* car.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Executive cars are classified as E-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] In the United States and several other countries, the equivalent categories are full-size car (not to be confused with the European category of "full-size luxury car") or *mid-size luxury* car.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The largest size of a luxury car is known as a *luxury saloon* in the United Kingdom and a *full-size luxury car* in the United States.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] These cars are classified as F-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Vehicles in this category are often the flagship models of luxury car brands.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Cars that prioritize handling or straight-line acceleration are called sports cars or performance cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] However the term "sports car" is also sometimes used specifically for lightweight two-seat cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Sports/performance cars can either be built on unique platforms or upgraded versions of regular cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The definitions for these categories are often blurred and a car may be a member of multiple categories.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Sports cars are designed to emphasize handling, performance, or the thrill of driving.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Sports cars originated in Europe in the early 1900s, with one of the first recorded usages of the term "sports car" being in *The Times* newspaper in the United Kingdom in 1919.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Sports cars started to become popular during the 1920s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The term was originally used for two-seat roadsters (cars without fixed roofs).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] However, since the 1970s the term has also been used for cars with fixed roofs (which were previously considered grand tourers).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] A *sports sedan* — also known as "sports saloon" — is a subjective term for a sedan/saloon car that is designed to have sporting performance or handling characteristics.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] A supercar – also called an exotic car – is a loosely defined description of certain high-performance sportscars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Since the 1990s or 2000s, the term "hypercar" has come into use for the highest-performing supercars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Passenger vehicles with off-road capability or styling features are often categorized as either off-road vehicles, sports utility vehicles, or crossover SUVs.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] There are no commonly agreed boundaries between these categories, and usage of the terms varies between countries.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The earliest type of passenger vehicle is called an "off-roader", "four-by-four" or "four-wheel drive".
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Off-road vehicles are usually more focused on off-road capability than SUVs and crossover SUVs (often compromising their on-road ride quality or handling).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Common features of off-road vehicles are four-wheel drive, high ground clearance, a body-on-frame (separate chassis) construction and low-range gearing.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] A sports utility vehicle (SUV) combines elements of road-going passenger vehicles with features from off-road vehicles, such as raised ground clearance and four-wheel drive.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] There is no common definition of an SUV, and usage varies between countries.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Some definitions claim that an SUV must be built on a light-truck chassis.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] However, a broader definition considers any vehicle with off-road design features as an SUV.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] In some countries — such as the United States — SUVs have been classified as "light trucks", resulting in more lenient regulations compared to passenger vehicles.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The predecessors to SUVs date back to military and low-volume models from the late 1930s, and the four-wheel drive station wagons / carryalls that began to be introduced in 1949.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The 1984 Jeep Cherokee (XJ) is considered to be the first SUV in the modern style.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Most SUVs produced today use unibody construction (as per passenger cars).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] However, in the past, many SUVs used body-on-frame construction.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] A crossover SUV— also called a crossover or CUV— is a type of sports utility vehicle (SUV) that uses a unibody construction.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Crossovers are often based on a platform shared with a passenger car, as a result, they typically have better comfort and fuel economy, but less off-road capability (many crossovers are sold without all-wheel drive) than truck-based SUVs, though more so than passenger four wheels.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] There are various inconsistencies about whether vehicles are considered crossovers or SUVs, therefore the term SUV is often used as a catch-all for both crossovers and SUVs.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] These classifications can be based on body style (e.g. sedan, coupe or hatchback), number of doors or seating capacity.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Government departments often create classification systems for taxation or regulating vehicle usage (e.g. vehicles that require a specific license or are restricted to certain roads).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Some jurisdictions may determine vehicle tax based upon environmental principles, such as the user pays principle.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] In Australia, the Federal Chamber of Automotive Industries publishes its classifications.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] A similar set of classes is used by the Canadian EPA.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The classification of a three-box vehicle (sedan) is determined by its length, while the classification of a two-box car (hatchback and SUV) or MPV is determined by its wheelbase.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] In the United Kingdom, a vehicle is taxed according to the vehicle's construction, engine, weight, type of fuel, and emissions, as well as the purpose for which it is used.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] In the United States, since 2010 the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety has used a formula it developed that takes into account a combination of both vehicle footprint (length times width) and weight.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The United States National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) separates vehicles into classes by the curb weight of the vehicle with standard equipment including the maximum capacity of fuel, oil, coolant, and air conditioning, if so equipped.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The United States Federal Highway Administration has developed a classification system used for automatically calculating road use tolls.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] There are two broad categories depending on whether the vehicle carries passengers or commodities.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Vehicles that carry commodities are further subdivided by the number of axles and number of units, including both power and trailer units.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA) has developed a classification system used to compare fuel economy among similar vehicles.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Passenger vehicles are classified based on a vehicle's total interior passenger and cargo volumes.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Trucks are classified based on their gross vehicle weight rating (GVWR).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Heavy-duty vehicles are not included in the EPA scheme.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Certain cities in the United States in the 1920s chose to exempt electric-powered vehicles because officials believed those vehicles did not cause "substantial wear upon the pavements".
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in North America.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Cars from these segments may also be sold in other countries.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to North America.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Muscle car is an American term for high-performance cars, usually rear-wheel drive and fitted with a large and powerful V8 engine.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The term originated for the 1960s and early 1970s special editions of mass-production cars which were designed for drag racing.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Pony car is an American class of automobile launched and inspired by the Ford Mustang in 1964.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] It broke all post-World War II automobile sales records, "creating the 'pony car' craze soon adopted by competitors." The term describes an affordable, compact, highly styled car with a sporty or performance-oriented image.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] A personal luxury car is a North American market segment for premium coupé or convertible produced from 1952–2007.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] These two-door cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Not prioritizing maximum interior space, interior volumes are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification, and exterior dimensions can exceed F-segment.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] A sporting version of an affordable compact car or a subcompact car.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] There is no precise definition and the description is applied for marketing purposes to a wide variety of models.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Cars began to be marketed as sport compacts in the mid-1980s when it was used for option packages on American-built coupes.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Since then, it has also been used for standalone sports car models and cars imported from Europe and Asia.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] However, sport compacts are not restricted to just hatchback body styles.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in Europe.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to Europe.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] A grand tourer (GT) is a car that is designed for high-speed and long-distance driving, due to a combination of performance and luxury attributes.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The most common format is a front-engine, rear-wheel-drive two-door coupé with either a two-seat or a 2+2 arrangement.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] The term derives from the Italian language phrase *gran turismo* which became popular in the English language from the 1950s, evolving from fast touring cars and streamlined closed sports cars during the 1930s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Hot hatch (shortened from hot hatchback) is a high-performance version of a mass-produced hatchback car.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] However, factory high-performance versions of hatchbacks have been produced since the 1970s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Front-mounted petrol engines, together with front-wheel drive, are the most common powertrain layout.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] However, all-wheel drive has become more commonly used since around 2010.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-classification] Most hot hatches are manufactured in Europe or Asia.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] A **car platform** is a shared set of common design, engineering, and production efforts, as well as major components, over a number of outwardly distinct models and even types of cars, often from different, but somewhat related, marques.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] It is practiced in the automotive industry to reduce the costs associated with the development of products by basing those products on a smaller number of platforms.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] This further allows companies to create distinct models from a design perspective on similar underpinnings.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] A car platform is not to be confused with a platform chassis, although such a chassis can be part of an automobile's design platform, as noted below.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] A basic definition of a platform in cars, from a technical point of view, includes underbody and suspensions (with axles) — where the underbody is made of the front floor, rear floor, engine compartment, and frame (reinforcement of underbody).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Platform sharing is a product development method where different products and the brand attached share the same components.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] The purpose with platform sharing is to reduce the cost and have a more efficient product development process.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] The companies gain on reduced procurement costs by taking advantage of the commonality of the components.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] However, this also limits their ability to differentiate the products and imposes a risk of losing the tangible uniqueness of the product.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] The companies have to make a trade-off between reducing their development costs and the degree of differentiation of the products.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Platform sharing is a practice commonly employed by various brands within a corporate group.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] The fundamental components of a shared platform typically include the chassis and the drive unit.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Platform sharing facilitates the efficient production and development of vehicles by leveraging common components across different models, thereby reducing costs and enhancing operational efficiency.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] One of the first car companies to use this product development approach was General Motors in 1908.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] General Motors used a single chassis for certain class of model across most of its brands like Chevrolet, Buick, Pontiac and Oldsmobile.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Later, Chrysler Corporation would do the same for Plymouth, DeSoto and Dodge cars.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Ford followed the same principle for Ford and Mercury in US markets.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] The chassis unit was common with many shared mechanical components while the exterior styling and interior trims were designed according to its individual brand and category.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Pictured below is the Nissan MS platform, where designs including 5-door hatchback, sedan, compact SUV and minivan were built on a common floor panel and many shared functional assemblies such as engine, transmission and chassis components.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Many vendors refer to this as **product or vehicle architecture**.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] The concept of product architecture is the scheme by which the function of a product is allocated to physical components.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] The car platform strategy has become important in new product development and in the innovation process.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] The finished products have to be responsive to market needs and to demonstrate distinctiveness while – at the same time – they must be developed and produced at low cost.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Adopting such a strategy affects the development process and also has an important impact on an automaker's organizational structure.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] A platform strategy also offers advantages for the globalization process of automobile firms.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Because automakers spend the majority of time and money on the development of platforms, platform sharing affords manufacturers the ability to cut costs on research and development by spreading it over several product lines.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Manufacturers are then able to offer products at a lower cost to consumers.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Additionally, economies of scale are increased, as is return on investment.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Originally, a "platform" was a literally shared chassis from a previously-engineered vehicle, as in the case for the Citroën 2CV platform chassis used by the Citroën Ami and Citroën Dyane, as well as the Volkswagen Beetle frame under the Volkswagen Karmann Ghia.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] These two manufacturers made different category of vehicles under using the same chassis design at different years though the primary vehicle was still in production.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] In the United States, platform sharing has been a common practice since the 1960s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] This was when GM used the same platform in the development of the Pontiac LeMans, the Buick Skylark, the Chevrolet Chevelle, and the Oldsmobile Cutlass.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] In the 1980s, Chrysler's K-cars all wore a badge with the letter "K" to indicate their shared platform.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] In later stages, the "K" platform was extended in wheelbase, as well as use for several of the Corporation's different models.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] In the same decade, Fiat and Saab jointly developed cars using the Type Four platform to compete with the German-dominated European executive car segment.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] General Motors used similar strategies with its "J" platform that debuted in mid-1981 in four of GM's divisions.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Subsequently, GM introduced its "A" bodies for the same four divisions using the same tread width/wheelbase of the "X" body platform, but with larger bodywork to make the cars seem larger, and with larger trunk compartments.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] They were popular through the 1980s, primarily.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Even Cadillac started offering a "J" body model called the Cimarron, a much gussied-up version of the other four brands' platform siblings.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] A similar strategy applied to what is known as the N-J-L platform, arguably the most prolific of GM's efforts on one platform.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Once more, GM's four lower-level divisions all offered various models on this platform throughout the 1980s and into the 1990s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] The 1988 Fiat Tipo was one of the first European cars utilizing a modular platform, also used for the Fiat Tempra.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Japanese carmakers have followed the platform sharing practice with Honda's Acura line, Nissan's Infiniti brand, and Toyota's Lexus marque, as the entry-level luxury models are based on their mainstream lineup.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] For example, the Lexus ES is essentially an upgraded and rebadged Toyota Camry.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] After Daimler-Benz merged with Chrysler, Chrysler engineers used several M-B platforms for new models including the Crossfire which was based on the M-B SLK roadster.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Other models that share platforms are the European Ford Focus, Mazda 3, and the Volvo S40.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Differences between shared models typically involve styling, including headlights, tail lights, and front and rear fascias.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Examples also involve differing engines and drivetrains.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Platform sharing *may* be less noticeable now; however, it is still very apparent.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Vehicle architectures primarily consist of "under the skin" components, and shared platforms can show up in unusual places, like the Nissan FM platform-mates Nissan 350Z marketed as a sports car and Infiniti FX positioned as a SUV.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] The Volkswagen A platform-mates such as the sports-oriented Audi TT and the economy-focused Volkswagen Golf also share much of their mechanical components but are visually entirely different.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Both the Volkswagen Group and Toyota have had much success building many well-differentiated vehicles from many marques, from the same platforms.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] One of the least conspicuous recent examples is the Chevy Trailblazer and Chevy SSR; both use the GMT-360 platform.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Platform sharing allows for fewer parts for different models of vehicles and therefore the task of inventorying those parts is greatly reduced.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Platform sharing allows manufacturers to cover many different market segments when a platform sharing strategy is implemented.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] They are essentially the same vehicles, but they are targeted as being in the mass-market, near luxury, and luxury vehicles segments.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Platform sharing allows manufacturers to design parts with fewer variation.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] A byproduct of this is increased quality, which results in lower defect rates.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Platform sharing allows manufacturers to design flexible platforms that can be tailored to a country's specific needs without compromising quality.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] It also allows for manufacturing standardization and improved logistics.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Platform sharing allows manufacturers to build/design differentiated products faster and cheaper.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] This is possible because the development and cost of the original platform have already been paid for.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Manufacturers that practice platform sharing have the ability to create several models based on the same design but with different names.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] This leads to the public looking over certain models and cannibalized sales from competing automakers with essentially similar products.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] The two elements of platforms are constant and non-constant.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] If the non-constant elements are not designed to be easily integrated into the constant elements of the platform, extensive and expensive changes will have to be made in order to make the elements compatible again.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Failure to do so negates the purpose of platform sharing in that it increases costs as opposed to reducing them.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Platform sharing has the ability to be used in too many different models.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] However, in the minds of the consumers, the products may be too similar and more expensive products may be perceived to be cheaper.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] For example, the perceived value of a "luxury" brand may be not as desirable if it is too similar to a mass-market version of the same platform.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] Conversely, platform sharing may increase the price of the economic models.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] The propensity for a higher number of recall is greatly increased with platform sharing.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/car-platform] If a defect is found in one model and that model shares its platform with nine other models, the recall would be magnified by ten thus costing the manufacturer more time and money to fix.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] A **center axle disconnect** system or CAD is an alternative to locking hubs.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] CAD systems are typically used in front drive axles on four wheel drive vehicles.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] A CAD system works by having an axle shaft (typically the longer shaft) split into two pieces.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] One piece is connected to the carrier, the other connected to the wheel.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] This reduces drag on the axle by allowing only the spider and side gears to spin, while the differential carrier, pinion and drive shaft are at rest (as is the inner portion of the disconnected long shaft and its associated side gear).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] The axle is engaged by connecting the two split axle shafts.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] The ends of the axles are typically splined and use a collar to connect the two shafts together by sliding over both shafts.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] Although a widely used system, this system is not as efficient as a system with locking hubs.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] A CAD system spins the axle shafts, spider gears, and side gears in the carrier during normal driving.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] Locking hubs disengage the axle at the wheels, allowing all of the axle to be at rest during normal driving.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] Nevertheless, a CAD system still makes for much less drag than having the axle completely locked in (which would spin the axles, differential, driveshaft and part of the internals of the transfer case).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] Like locking hubs, the CAD system is designed to improve fuel efficiency of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] Other, often debated, benefits of CAD systems are reduced vibration, axle wear, and noise, as well as improved steering and drivability.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] Unlike locking hubs, CAD systems are generally automatic and engaged when the vehicle is placed in four wheel drive.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] Due to the lack of driver control over the CAD, it is not as well known to the public as manual locking hubs are (but no different from automatic locking hubs in terms of driver involvement, and manual hubs are rare on modern 4x4 vehicles).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] Locking hubs are obtrusive and damage can occur that can cause the four wheel drive system to fail — damage that would not be an issue in a CAD system.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] However CAD systems are mostly vacuum controlled and damage can occur to the vacuum system and to the CAD itself.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] Rotting of vacuum lines will cause the four wheel drive system to fail — damage that would not be an issue with locking hubs.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] In 2002 it was phased out of the 2500 and 3500, leaving some late models without a CAD system.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/center-axle-disconnect] Ram 2013 model year trucks began using a CAD system again, this time electronically controlled instead of vacuum.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The **Chevrolet K5 Blazer** is a full-size sport-utility vehicle (SUV) that was marketed by Chevrolet from the 1969 to 1994 model years.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] A variant of the C/K truck line, the K5 Blazer is a shortened version of the half-ton pickup line.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For its first two generations, the model line was a half-cab pickup truck fitted with a removable rear top (effectively making it a three-door station wagon); the final generation was fitted with permanent rear bodywork.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Initially offered solely as a 4x4, the K5 Blazer was also marketed with a rear-wheel drive configuration.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Alongside the longer-wheelbase Chevrolet/GMC Suburban wagon-style SUV (offered with three rows of seating and second-row doors), the K5 Blazer was marketed by GMC from 1970 to 1991 as the GMC Jimmy (reflecting a shorthand nickname for the brand).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Though the K5 prefix was used on Chevrolet badging until 1988, GM never internally referred the Blazer/Jimmy as such.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Following the 1983 release of the S-Series Blazer/Jimmy, to avoid market confusion, GM officially changed the model lines to "Chevrolet Full-Size Blazer" and "GMC K-Jimmy" (after 1986, V-Jimmy), though they are often unofficially still addressed as "K5" to avoid confusion.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For 1992, General Motors redesigned its entire full-size SUV lineup, with GMC renaming the Jimmy as the GMC Yukon.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The full-size Blazer was replaced for 1995, as the Chevrolet Tahoe inaugurated a shorter-wheelbase variant of the Suburban.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Currently, GM markets the Tahoe and Yukon alongside the Cadillac Escalade, and later resurrected the "Blazer" name for a midsize crossover SUV while Kia now uses the "K5" name for an unrelated midsize sedan.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Chevrolet developed the first-generation K5 Blazer to market its own recreational off-road vehicle, competing against the International Scout and the Ford Bronco.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] While competing against the Jeep CJ-5, the design was also developed to improve its on-road capabilities against all of its competitors.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The half-ton K10 pickup truck served as a basis, as designers shortened its wheelbase from 115 inches to 104 inches.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Though larger than both the Bronco and the Scout (and far larger than the Jeep), the use of the C/K platform for the "K5" Blazer led to multiple design breakthroughs that proved popular.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Coinciding with its larger exterior size, the Blazer also had more cargo space, and better on-road handling (stemming from its wider-set wheels and longer wheelbase).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Additionally, the Blazer shared a large degree of commonality with standard C/K pickup trucks, allowing for lower production costs (and price).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] While base-trim K5 Blazers were intended as spartan vehicles (with both a top and passenger seat considered options), the commonality with the C/K allowed for the addition of optional "luxury" features, including automatic transmissions, radios, and air conditioning.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] In line with its competitors, the Blazer was built as an open-roof vehicle, with buyers selecting a choice of either a convertible soft top or a wagon-style removable hard top.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] By 1970, the Blazer would overtake its rivals in the marketplace.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For 1974, Chrysler introduced the Dodge Ramcharger (a shortened Dodge D100 pickup truck) and Jeep introduced the Jeep Cherokee (a shortened Jeep Gladiator, alongside the Jeep Wagoneer).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For 1978, Ford introduced a second-generation Bronco to compete directly against the K5 Blazer, moving it to a shortened F100 platform).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For its first model year (1969), the K5 Blazer was available with part-time four-wheel drive only.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] As an option, a removable hardtop or a soft convertible-top could be specified; passenger seats also were optional on the base model.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For 1970, a rear-wheel drive model was added, and the truck was also rebadged as the GMC Jimmy.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] There were four choices for power plants, matching the contemporaneous pickup truck options: the *250* straight-6, the *292* straight-6, the *307* V8, and the *350* V8.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] There was also a choice between a three-speed automatic transmission, the Turbo-Hydramatic TH350, or one of two fully-synchronized manual transmissions: a three-speed, or a four-speed (SM465), which included a "granny gear" low-ratio 6.55:1 first gear.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The 350 was offered only with the SM465 or TH350; manual locking front hubs were optional.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The four-wheel drive version had a solid front axle and used leaf springs front and rear.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The two-wheel drive version came with independent front suspension and rear trailing arms, both with coil springs.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Both versions used drum brakes on all four wheels until 1971, when the entire GM light truck line was fitted with front discs as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Two transfer cases were offered: the Dana 20, available only with the manual transmissions, or the NP-205, available with both types of transmissions.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The Blazer had 8 inches (200 mm) of ground clearance and an approach angle of 35°.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For 1973, GM's line of full-size trucks was redesigned and updated; internally, GM named this the "Rounded Line" generation, while the public nickname was "square body".
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Although rear-wheel-drive Blazers were manufactured until 1982, the majority sold were four-wheel drive.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] With the standard 250 I6 and automatic transmission, a 1974 K5 Blazer returned fuel economy of 13.69 mpg‑US (17.18 L/100 km; 16.44 mpg‑imp) at the same speed.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The 1973–75 K5 Blazers were equipped with a removable convertible top.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] In 1976, a half-cab design was introduced and used until 1991.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The weight of the large glass panel was rumored to be a liability as the manual crank gears wore prematurely and the electric motor was prone to frequent overheating and subsequent failure.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] This also included the electric motor drive cable which goes to the window regulator to the motor (similar in design to a speedometer cable), which usually would fail under heavy abuse.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Another feature of the K5 Blazer tailgate was the safety switch connected to the electric motor which prevented the rear window from being raised if the tailgate was unlatched.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Compared to the first generation K5 Blazer, the Rounded Line K5 grew by 7 in (180 mm) overall, on a 2.5 in (64 mm) longer wheelbase.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The styling was refreshed in 1981, mirroring the changes introduced on the 1981 C/K pickups, most visible in the front end with available stacked dual square headlamps and reduced weight.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] GM temporarily changed the usual "C/K" designation to "R" and "V" for the 1987 through 1991 model years.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] This was done to avoid confusion with the GMT400-based Chevrolet C/K pickup trucks, which were introduced in 1988, during the overlap period.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Although the GMT400 trucks were introduced in the spring of 1987 as a 1988 model, the K5 Blazer, Suburban, and crew-cab trucks retained the earlier platform until 1991.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] In 1988, four new colors were introduced: Bright Blue Metallic, Forest Green Metallic, Light Mesa Brown Metallic, and Dark Mesa Brown Metallic.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] More new features for 1988 included a fixed mast antenna in place of the old windshield antenna, a trip odometer as part of the gauge package cluster, and an improved pulse windshield wiper control.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Also, helping to reduce air leaks in the doors was a new door handle seal.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Also in 1988, General Motors eliminated the "K5" emblems.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] In late 1988 for the 1989 model year, the front grille was changed to resemble the squared-off ones used on the GMT400 series of pickups.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The 1989 Blazer had new base and up-level grilles, as well as new headlight bezels, body side moldings, and front bumper rub strips.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] New for 1989 was the introduction of an all-new base coat/clear coat paint.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For the 1990 model year, all Blazers now had a standard rear-wheel anti-lock braking system.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] A new electronic speedometer system, with a six-digit odometer on the dashboard, was also introduced for 1990, along with non-asbestos brake linings.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] A new brake warning light on the dashboard was also introduced for 1990.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The Blazer body also used double-sided, galvanized exterior sheet metal.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] A new option for 1990 was power mirrors.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Three-point shoulder harness also become standard for rear passengers.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The rear seat armrest were eliminated from rear seat to make room for shoulder belts and pads were added to the wheel housings.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For 1991, two new exterior colors, Brilliant Blue and Slate Metallic were offered.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The K5 Blazer was fitted with a 250 cu in (4.1 L) inline-six as standard through 1982.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Available engines included small-block V8s of 305, 307, 350, or 400 cubic inches (5.0, 5.0, 5.7, and 6.6 liters), and a 6.2 L Detroit Diesel V8.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The six-cylinder Blazer was not recommended for towing.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Since 1981 (in the wake of the 1973 Arab Oil Embargo and the 1979 energy crisis), Chevrolet and GMC used the smaller displacement 305s with a 9.2:1 compression ratio.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] These engines produced nearly as much torque as the 350, giving a similar driving feel.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] However, these power plants were underpowered and prone to detonation (engine knocking), especially with the electronic spark control module.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] To achieve the 9.2:1 compression ratio, the cylinder head chambers were smaller, measuring 56 cc instead of 76 cc.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] After 1987, when throttle-body injection was introduced in the truck engines, the 350 was made the standard power plant.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Corporate 10-bolt axles were upgraded to 30-spline axle shafts from previous 28-spline shafts in 1989.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] In addition, the standard L05 5.7-liter V8 now had one serpentine accessory drive belt in place of the older multi-belt accessory drive setup.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] 1989 was the first year for the NP241 transfer case and also the only year for speedometer-cable driven version of the NP241.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The 5.7 liter V8 (L05) engine was improved for 1990 with the addition of improved oil control rings, a redesigned rear crankshaft seal, a new camshaft sprocket design, non-asbestos intake manifold gaskets, and heavy-duty intake valves.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The TBI (throttle body injection) system used on the Blazer's standard 5.7-liter V8 had longer throttle shaft bearings, new throttle return springs, and improved fuel mixture distribution.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The 5.7 liter V8 also had new heavy-duty intake valves and powdered metal camshaft sprockets.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Standard on all engines was a lighter more powerful 100-amp CS130 alternator.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] 1973–1980 Blazers used the gear-driven part-time NP-205 transfer case (mostly mated to the SM465 manual transmission and some TH350s) or the chain-driven full-time NP-203 transfer case (mated to the TH350 automatic) and Dana 44 front/12-bolt rear axle combination through 1980.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Starting in 1981 used the chain-driven NP208 transfer case (NP241 after 1988) with front 10-bolt/rear 10-bolt axle combinations until 1991.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] There is an overlap of 12-bolt rears into the early 1980s, while the 10-bolt front axle was phased into production in the late 1970s.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For the 1992 model year, the third-generation Blazer made its debut, as GM moved its full-size SUVs to the GMT400 architecture (four years after its C/K debut).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Chevrolet dropped the K5 prefix completely, with the "Full-Size Blazer" retained from the R/V-series.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The model line grew modestly in size (3 inches in length, 6 inches in wheelbase), but underwent significant changes to its configuration.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] In place of the long-running half-cab pickup, the Blazer was now a three-door wagon, sharing its bodywork aft of the doors with the Suburban (losing both its removable roof and retractable tailgate glass).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] In a branding change, GMC dropped the Jimmy name from its counterpart for 1992 (giving the name to its midsize SUV), renaming it as the **GMC Yukon**.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The Blazer was named "Four Wheeler of the Year" in 1992 by *Four Wheeler* magazine.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For 1993, the model line took part in further branding changes.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The GMT400 Blazer dropped its "Full-Size" prefix, becoming the Chevrolet Blazer, as the GMT330 S10 Blazer was renamed the "S-Blazer".
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For 1992, a 210 horsepower (157 kW) 350 cu in (5.7 L) small-block V8 with throttle-body fuel injection was the only engine offered with the Blazer/Yukon (the 6.2L diesel V8 was discontinued as an option).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For 1994, a 180 horsepower (134 kW) 6.5 L Detroit Diesel turbodiesel V8 was introduced as an option; the 6.5 L engine was offered only with an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] All versions were fitted with an independent front suspension and solid rear axle with leaf springs; four-wheel-drive versions had torsion bars on the front, while two-wheel-drive versions had coil springs.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For 1995, Chevrolet followed suit with GMC, renaming the GMT400 Chevrolet Blazer as the Chevrolet Tahoe (with the midsize S-Blazer adopting the Blazer nameplate).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Serving as the counterpart of the GMC Yukon, the 1995 Tahoe continued to be offered as a three-door counterpart of the Suburban.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The same year, GM offered a third variant of the GMT400 SUVs, with an all-new five-door Tahoe/Yukon, sized between the two traditional configurations (with a two-row interior).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] After 1997, GMC discontinued the three-door Yukon, with Chevrolet discontinuing the three-door Tahoe after 1999; as of current production, GM has not since produced a three-door full-size SUV.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For 1998 and 1999, respectively, the five-door Tahoe served as the basis for the GMC Yukon Denali and the Cadillac Escalade, the first full-size luxury SUVs produced by GM.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Around 1976, a prototype K5 Blazer was used as a testbed for a military CUCV vehicle built by Vic Hickey, father of the HUMVEE.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Between 1983 and 1987, what is known as the M1009 CUCV was the production militarized version of the civilian K5.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The differences are the lack of an air conditioner, an additional leaf spring in the suspension, a hybrid 12/24 V electrical system (described in detail below), blackout headlights, front mounted brush guard, a rifle rack, and special paint jobs.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] A majority of them are painted olive drab green or in the woodland camouflage pattern, though some vehicles that saw desert use were painted tan.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] All M1009s, including its derivatives, are powered with the 6.2 L Diesel power plant.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The M1009s have a split 24/12 V electrical system.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Most of the truck actually runs on 12 V.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] It has two separate 12 V alternators and batteries wired in series, with only the glow plug system, injection pump, starter, and jumper cable jack being wired to the 24 V terminals; everything else in the truck runs on 12 V.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The glow plugs are actually 12 V glow plugs with a resistor pack on the firewall to drop the 24 V down to 12 V.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] This resistor pack can be bypassed and the glow plugs run directly off of the 12 V battery.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] If this is done and the 24 V starter is replaced with a standard 12 V starter, the second alternator is no longer needed (If this is done then the military 24 V slave adapter in the grille will need to be disconnected as well).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Some decommissioned M1009s end up in law enforcement use (e.g., with the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department) or sold through government auctions, but a handful are still in use by the National Guard.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] In 1976, GM collaborated with recreational vehicle manufacturer Chinook Mobilodge to offer modified versions of the Blazer and Jimmy with a permanently-fixed popup truck camper unit.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Approximately 1,800 *Blazer Chalet* and *Jimmy Casa Grande* vehicles were built over two years of production.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] With the top raised, interior headroom increased from 59 to 79.5 in (1,500 to 2,020 mm).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The integrated camper allows occupants to walk through from the cab to the rear living quarters.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] In 1977, suggested retail price of the base model was US$9,426 (equivalent to $50,000 in 2025), but options could increase the price to $13,000.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The Yukon GT was introduced in 1993 as a sport-appearance trim variant of the third generation GMC Yukon (previously Jimmy) as a "Sport Equipment Package", option code BYP.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] It is equipped with four-wheel-drive and aluminum wheels; the GT package was available exclusively with the 350 in3 (5.7L) *L05* V8.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] A 5-speed manual transmission is standard, but the automatic transmission can be selected.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Visually, the GT was rendered in a monochromatic color scheme by painting the grille, bumpers, trim, and fender flares the same color as the body, which was available in black or dark garnet.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] It matched the appearance of the contemporaneously marketed high-performance GMC Syclone truck and Typhoon SUV, but unlike the smaller vehicles, the Yukon GT did not have any special engine tuning.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The K5 Blazer-E followed the Chevrolet E-10 Concept, a similar "electromod" restoration and electrification project that converted a 1962 C-10 pickup with a Bolt-derived EV powertrain, shown at SEMA 2019.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Other "electromod" restorations with EV powertrains that followed the K5 Blazer-E include the 2021 Hyundai Heritage Series and 2021 Ford F-100 Eluminator.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The Blazer-E retains its original driveshafts, axles, and transfer case, and uses a more powerful 200 hp (150 kW) Bolt traction motor instead of the 400 cu.in.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] V8, which had an estimated output of 175 hp (130 kW) using modern ratings.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The Bolt's 60 kW-hr battery pack is bolted into the cargo area of the K5 Blazer-E.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Aftermarket components were used to add power steering, generate vacuum for the vintage braking system, and control the gauges, with the fuel gauge converted to indicate state of charge instead.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] For the 2019 SEMA show, a customized 2018 Chevrolet Tahoe was restyled by Flat Out Autos as an homage to the first generation K5 Blazer.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Dubbed the "Retro Tahoe", it was built to honor the Blazer's 50th anniversary.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] Steps to complete the customization include replacement of the stock exterior sheetmetal, a carbon fiber rear hatch, and machined aluminum door handles; four were built for members of the Abu Dhabi royal family.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/chevrolet-k5-blazer] The following year, the same shop showed a modified two-door K5 Blazer homage using a sectioned Tahoe chassis.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The **Dodge Ramcharger** is a large sport utility vehicle built by Dodge from 1974 to 1993, based on a shortened-wheelbase version of the Dodge D series/Ram pickup chassis.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] A Plymouth version, named the **Plymouth Trail Duster,** offered from 1974 to 1981, was Plymouth's only SUV.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The Ramcharger was mostly produced as a two-door, 4×4 vehicle, although a two-wheel-drive version was available.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] As a full-size SUV, it competed with the Chevrolet K5 Blazer and the 1978–1996 Ford Bronco.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The Ramcharger was discontinued at the end of the 1993 model year in North America.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] In Mexico, however, production continued until 1996.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] It was then brought back from 1999 to 2001, still as a two-door SUV and sharing the design of the contemporary Ram pickup.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] Approximately 30,000 were produced, with all examples being two-wheel-drive only.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] In November 2023, Stellantis announced that the Ramcharger nameplate would be revived for a plug-in hybrid and extended-range electric vehicle truck version of the 2025 Ram 1500.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] During development, it was known as the "Rhino." The Ramcharger/Trail Duster were built using a version of the Dodge Ram's Chrysler AD platform with a 9 inches (230 mm) shorter wheelbase.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] Originally available in four-wheel-drive exclusively, a rear-wheel-drive only version was available starting in 1975.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The 1974 through 1980 models came without a roof, with a dealer-installed fabric top, or an optional removable steel roof with a flip-up rear tailgate window.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The early 1974 year model differs from the others in that its door pillars are attached to the removable roof.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The "half doors" were used up to the build date of June 10, 1974; afterwards, the roof was changed to use normal pickup-style doors.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] Marketed as a basic utility vehicle, only the driver's seat was standard equipment with the passenger seat optional up to 1976.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] Also available was an insulated center console for keeping items cool when filled with ice.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The Ramcharger was entered in rallying and placed first in the 1975 Sno*Drift event.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The standard engine was a 225 cu in (3.7 L) Slant Six.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] 318 cu in (5.2 L) and 360 cu in (5.9 L) versions of the "LA" series Chrysler small-block V8 were available, along with the larger big-block "B" and "RB" wedge series in 400 cu in (6.6 L) and 440 cu in (7.2 L).
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The Ramcharger and Trail Duster followed the D-series pickup's 1981 redesign into the Ram and is considered the second generation.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] They had an egg crate-style grille which was used until the 1986 model year, when the front was redesigned to the crosshair grille that remains common on many Dodges today.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] In 1991, there were another batch of grill changes that lasted until 1993 when American Ramcharger production stopped.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The second-generation trucks had a few different trim and interior option levels, but not much changed over the years.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] These models had a non-removable welded steel top instead of the removable top.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The Trail Duster was only available for one year with the Ram design and steel non-removable top, as it was dropped after the 1981 model year.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] From 1981 through 1987, all models were carbureted, but in 1988, throttle-body fuel injection (TBI) was added to the 318 cu in (5.2 L) V8 engine.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] Fuel injection was added to the 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 engine in 1989.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] In 1992, the multiport fuel-injected Magnum 318 was the standard engine, while the LA 360 with TBI was still offered as an option.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] In 1993, the Magnum 360 replaced the LA engine.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] Many manual transmissions were offered throughout the years, starting with the A-230 three-speed and ending with the A-535 five-speed in 1992.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The NP435 "granny gear" 4 speed was the most common in 4WD models, as well as the close ratio version, the NP445.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] In 1988 the clutch was converted from a mechanical linkage to a hydraulic system.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] Automatic transmission models had the Chrysler Loadflite TF-727A or B until, in 1991, it was replaced with the A-500/A-518 four-speed.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] An all-wheel-drive NP-203 transfer case was standard until 1980, when it was replaced with the part-time NP-208.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] This was supplanted by the NP-241 in 1988.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] Axles were Dana 44 front and 9.25" or 8.25" Chrysler corporate rear.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] AWD models (1973–1979) were equipped with the full-time version of the Dana 44 that had no provision for locking hubs and had a front wheel bearing design with a somewhat dubious reputation.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] In 1978, when the part-time 4WD system was introduced, the front Dana 44 was equipped with a more conventional front wheel bearing design and automatic locking hubs.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] Late in the 1984 model year, the Dana 44 was switched to a CAD (Center Axle Disconnect) version.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The CAD Dana 44 was vacuum-actuated by a switch on the transfer case and powered by engine vacuum.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The CAD Dana 44 was carried on until the end of Ramcharger production in 1993.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The vacuum switch on the transfer case would occasionally fail and either leave the CAD engaged or not engage the CAD at all.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] Limited-slip differentials were available for the 9¼" rear axle.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The AWD versions used a 5 on 4.5" wheel bolt circle and the part-time 4WD models used a 5 on 5.5" bolt circle.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] 2WD models used the 5 on 4.5" wheel bolt circle, which was changed to the 5 on 5.5" pattern in 1985.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The Ramcharger continued to be sold in Mexico until 1996, with minor running changes from the last version sold in the U.S. and Canada in 1993.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] The third generation Ramcharger was produced in Mexico from 1998 for the 1999 model year, based on the same platform as the Dodge Ram pickup and sharing most of its componentry with the Ram as well.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] It had also shared some of its parts and components with the third-generation Chrysler minivans (Chrysler Town & Country, Dodge Caravan/Plymouth Voyager) as well.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] It was only sold in Mexico where the previous-generation Ramcharger had been successful.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] It was available in the ST, SLT, SLT Plus, and Sport trim levels.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] Powered by the 318 cu in (5.2 L) or 360 cu in (5.9 L) Magnum V8 engine and offered exclusively with rear-wheel drive, it was discontinued after the 2001 model year.
[src:dodge-ramcharger/dodge-ramcharger] One of the features of this generation was a small third-row folding seat in the cargo area that faced sideways, making it less practical for long trips.
